author: @edwardseverinsen5598
textdisplay:
I'm enjoying Vue thus far. The only hang up for me at the moment is using the same Vue app for multiple instances of essentially the same "object" on a webpage. For instance: Having a ListView in Django that displays multiple blog posts per page, with the body of their text being truncated to say 30 words and using Vue to expand the post body upon clicking.

What I've had to do so far to work around this is use the {% for %} tag in my Django template and create a unique Vue app per blog post on the page. Which because I'm only showing 3 per page using pagination, doesn't have a noticeable performance impact, but seems hacky and like it may be a problem down the line.

Thus far I have not a found a concrete answer for using multiple instances of the same "app" in Vue across multiple elements. Being able to use a Vue app like a class with predetermined data variable names with assignable contents would be the whole package tbh. I just can't seem to find anyone talking about how to do this which honestly baffles me.

author: @neelsb7889
textdisplay:
Hi. Thanks for your time and efforts in making these tutorials for creating terminal games with Python and blessed. Unfortunately neither of your snake variations run in my Windows 10 "terminal" (command prompt) with Python 3.10.7. When I run the "you're the food" variation, immediately upon pressing an arrow key on the keyboard, I get "woah you won!! how did you do it?!" without seeing any of the "graphics" (actually saw nothing) on screen or playing at all. With your "standard" snake game, upon starting it and pressing an arrow key, I get:

score: 1 - speed: 3.2
Traceback (most recent call last):
File "C:\Users\user1\coding\py\csdojo\snake-terminal-blessed.py", line 91, in <module>
heading = world[head[0]][head[1]]
IndexError: list index out of range

Any ideas about what might be causing these problems and if/how I could try to fix them? And... would you consider sharing your curses version of the snake game, so new Python learners like me could see how the code differs between using curses vs blessed?

Edit: Apparently my Windows 10 command prompt can not display the unicode characters you used in the code to display the borders, snake and food... so it just displays nothing and gets confused. I simply replaced the special characters with regular ASCII characters in your variables BORDER = '#'
BODY = 'O'
SPACE = ' '
APPLE = '*'

and it works... then I tried my luck in replacing the BORDER character with a unicode block character '\u2593' and that also works fine. So I will experiment more with which characters Windows 10 can and can not display in the command line, to "upgrade" the "graphics" somewhat from plain ASCII :D

author: @soisauce364
textdisplay:
Page not found (404)
Request Method: POST
Request URL: http://127.0.0.1:8000/todo/addTodo/
Using the URLconf defined in todoapp.urls, Django tried these URL patterns, in this order:

admin/
todo/
addTodo/
The current path, todo/addTodo/, didn't match any of these.

You're seeing this error because you have DEBUG = True in your Django settings file. Change that to False, and Django will display a standard 404 page.

Please help me improve? (the code works) CS Dojo rocks!!!!


def LCSmemo(s1, s2, i1, i2):
memo = [[None] * len(s2) for _ in range(len(s1))]

return helper(s1, s2, i1, i2, memo)


def helper(s1, s2, i1, i2, memo):
if i1 == len(s1) or i2 == len(s2):

return ''

if memo[i1][i2] is not None:
return memo[i1][i2]

if s1[i1] == s2[i2]:
memo[i1][i2] = s1[i1] + helper(s1, s2, i1+1, i2+1, memo)
return memo[i1][i2]
else:
memo[i1][i2] = max(helper(s1, s2, i1, i2+1, memo), helper(s1, s2, i1+1, i2, memo))
return memo[i1][i2]


print(LCSmemo('Jeez, I am waiting for snow.', "Jeez, I have been waiting for snow.", 0, 0))

author: @lipan2757
textdisplay:
Hey YK!

I'm an iOS developer in Canada, recently I've been looking into applying for large tech companies and your videos have been very helpful! Below is my implementation of your method in swift. Given swift Arrays do not allow for nil values I've used a dictionary (hash table) for memo instead. It'd be great if you or anyone from the community can take a look at my implementation and see if there is anything I can improve on. Also, I was wondering if there is a bottom-up approach, through iteration, to solve this problem like the one you used to solve Fibonacci. Much appreciated!

func lscMemo(first: String, second: String) -> String {

var memo: [[Int]: String] = [:]
var callCount = 0

func lsc(s1: [String], s2: [String], i1: Int, i2: Int) -> String {

callCount += 1

if i1 == s1.count || i2 == s2.count {
return ""
}

if s1[i1] == s2[i2] {
let key = [i1, i2]
if let cachedValue = memo[key] {
return cachedValue
}

let result = s1[i1] + lsc(s1: s1, s2: s2, i1: i1 + 1, i2: i2 + 1)

memo[key] = result
return result

}

let keyA = [i1 + 1, i2]
let keyB = [i1, i2 + 1]

var resultA: String!
var resultB: String!

if let cachedValueA = memo[keyA] {
resultA = cachedValueA
}

else {
resultA = lsc(s1: s1, s2: s2, i1: i1 + 1, i2: i2)
memo[keyA] = resultA
// print("a:", resultA!)

}

if let cachedValueB = memo[keyB] {
resultB = cachedValueB
}

else {
resultB = lsc(s1: s1, s2: s2, i1: i1, i2: i2 + 1)
memo[keyB] = resultB
// print("b:", resultB!)
}

// print("callCount:", callCount)
return resultA.count > resultB.count ? resultA : resultB
}

return lsc(s1: first.map { String ($0) }, s2: second.map { String ($0) }, i1: 0, i2: 0)

// if case insensitive
// return lsc(s1: first.lowercased().map { String ($0) }, s2: second.lowercased().map { String ($0) }, i1: 0, i2: 0)

}

author: @magno5157
textdisplay: The trick is to think of the problem as a finite state machine or a graph in general, where an edge represents an option or a valid move, and a node represents a sub-state of the problem. A sub-state can be solved only after solving all of the sub-sub-states that can be reached by traversing all of the edges that originate from that sub-state.

One correction to your explanation:
If you have a variable that being defined as int8 for example, it will be stored in the memory using a single byte. Then the conversion from 8 bits to 32 bits (for a 32-bit processor) should be done before any processing on that variable. (So saving some memory, but it may slightly increase processing time because of the additional step of converting the int8 to int32)

package main

type Node struct {
data int
next *Node

node = node.next
}

}

author: @goldener-reiter
textdisplay:
Nice, excellent, brilliant, amazing video. Here's my solution, implemented in Java:

public class Main {
public static void main(String[] args) {
Node head = new Node(6);
Node nodeB = new Node(3);
Node nodeC = new Node(4);
Node nodeD = new Node(2);

head.next = nodeB;
nodeB.next = nodeC;
nodeC.next = nodeD;

System.out.println("The number of nodes are " + countNodes(head));
}

static int countNodes(Node head){
int count = 0;
Node auxNode = head;
while(auxNode.next != null){
count++;
auxNode = auxNode.next;
}
return count;
}
}

The static method receives a Type Node object, saves it into an auxiliar Object, while the next Object referred by the Link List is not null, it keeps adding 1 to the count and jumping into the next Node.

I hope it helps. Cheers!

author: @itsamemario6588
textdisplay:
Heyo, here's my Python 3.11 solution to the count nodes method at 11:47. It uses __future__.annotations to allow the Node class init to type hint itself, and typing.Any to type hint Anything for the data attribute. The program at the bottom generates both a list of nodes, wherein each appended node also becomes the next_node attribute of the most recently appended node. So, you can access the nodes by iterating through the list or by recursively accessing next_node attribute. I felt it was in the spirit of linked-lists to do recursion. I used a list to "collect" the nodes on a flat level because, if I hadn't, I don't know how I would add a node to the next_node element at the end of the list. Like, I'd have to make a function to recursively run through the linked-list from head every time until it found a null next_node and then create the new node there? That sounds super inefficient. I'd much rather have them collected in a flat list like this, but maybe I'm not understanding their use quite yet.

####################################################
# Start of program
# Python 3.11 code, all base packages
####################################################

from _future_ import annotations
from typing import Any

class Node:
def __init__(self, data : Any, next_node : Node = None ) -> None:
self.data = data
self.next_node = next_node

def __str__(self) -> str:
return f"node:: data: {self.data}, next_node: ||{self.next_node}"

def count_nodes(head : Node) -> int:
count = 1
iter_node = head

while iter_node.next_node._class_ == Node:
count += 1
iter_node = iter_node.next_node

return count

if _name_ == "__main__":

import random

head_node : Node = Node(data="CS Dojo is the first beer")

nodes_list : list[Node] = [head_node]

for i in nodes_list:
print(i)

for i in range(random.randint(1,6)):
new_node = Node(data=f"{i+2} bottles of beer on the wall") # +2 because this is the second node in the linked-list
nodes_list[-1].next_node = new_node
nodes_list.append(new_node)

print(f"There are {count_nodes(head_node)} many nodes this time\n")

for n in nodes_list:
print(n,"\n")

####################################################
# End of program
####################################################

author: @andreandrews6237
textdisplay:
I'm late but here goes:
yes, the return statement means 'stop', but stop once all code is run and your result is ready. because you're making a function call, your code will return the END of that function call. so it will go as far as the final return and then return the final result AFTER all function calls have been made.

so return func(n - 1) will work like this:

func(4) -> func(3) -> func(2) -> func(1) and lets just say you have a conditional that says if n <=1 return 1. It hits that conditional and returns the results back up the chain. Hope this helped

SPOILER ALERT!!!




In case somebody is wondering for a solution of the frog problem. It was at least 1 hour past until I figured out the solution. Here it is: (JavaScript-based). Feel free to point out if I'm mistaken.

// (frog) |--o--o--o--|
function countFrogRoutesTroughRiver(riverLength) {
// COUNTS LAST STEPS POSSIBLE AS 1 (does not distinguish 1-2 step at last iteration)

// steps possible: 1-step and 2-step
if (riverLength <= 1) return 1;
let counter = 0;
counter += countFrogRoutesTroughRiver(riverLength - 1); // short step
counter += countFrogRoutesTroughRiver(riverLength - 2); // long step
return counter;
}

console.log(countFrogRoutesTroughRiver(11)); // 144

Hi , thank you for your valuable videos. Actually i have basic knowledge of all the concepts. When i am taking coding questions, i am stuck with representation of converting problem into coding representation. i can think of my solution. but i start to write code. i am stuck with how we represent the problem as array or make list of some classes with properties like that. can u help me to resolve this.

Merging bubbles
Alice is playing with bubbles. She is standing at point (0, 0) and has created N bubbles. Each bubble can be characterized by there parameters:

v: denoting the size of the bubble
x: denoting the x coordinate of the bubble
y: denoting the y coordinate of the bubble
The following process will take place as long as there are two or more bubbles left:

Alice will choose the bubble closest to her (in case there are multiple options for a bubble she will choose the largest one among them). (Note: Here distance between two points (x1, y1) and (x2, y2) is equal to
After choosing the first bubble, similarly, she will choose the second bubble from the bubbles left.
Let the two bubbles chosen have parameters as [ v1, x1, y1 ] (first bubble) and [ v2, x2, y2 ] (second bubble) respectively .
She will merge the two bubbles chosen and a new bubble with parameters [ v1+v2, x1 - x2, y1 - y2 ] will be formed.
You are given array Arr containing the characteristics of the N bubbles.

Task

Determine the coordinates of the last bubble left after the process ends.

Notes

Assume 1-based indexing.
There could be multiple bubbles at the same point.
Explanation

Assumptions

N = 4
Arr = [ [9,1,0] , [4,9,0] , [12,0,1], [15,4,0] ]
Approach

There are two bubbles closest to Alice: [9, 1, 0] and [12, 0, 1] and among these the larger bubble (i.e [12, 0, 1] ) is choosen as the first bubble, So [9, 1, 0] will be choosen as the second bubble. The new bubble formed after merging these two bubbles is [21, -1, 1]. The new array of bubbles will be [ [4, 9, 0] , [15, 4, 0] , [21, -1, 1] ].
Now, the bubbles [21, -1, 1] and [15, 4, 0] will be chosen and the new resulting bubble will be [36, -5, 1].
Finally, bubbles [36, -5, 1] and [4, 9, 0] are chosen and the new bubble formed will be [40, -14, 1].
Now there is only one bubble left at coordinates (-14, 1) and this is the answer.
Function description

Complete the function solve provided in the editor. This function takes the following 2 parameters and returns the required answer:

N: Represents the size of array Arr
Arr: Represents the elements of array Arr
Input format

Note: This is the input format that you must use to provide custom input (available above the Compile and Test button).

The first line contains T denoting the number of test cases. T also specifies the number of times you have to run the solve function on a different set of inputs.
For each test case:
The first line contains N denoting the size of array Arr.
Each of the next N lines contains 3 space-separated integers. The ith line denotes the characteristics of the ith bubble: [v,x,y].
Output format
For each test case in a new line, print the coordinates of the last bubble.

Constraints

Approach

The bubble closest to Alice is [2, 1, 0] and the second closest bubble is [3, -2, -1] , after merging these two bubbles the new bubble formed will be [5, 3, 1]. Now Arr=[ [5, 3, 1], [5, 3, 4] , [8, 2, 2] ]
Now, the bubble [8, 2, 2] is chosen as the first bubble and [5, 3, 1] as the second. The new bubble formed after merging these two bubbles will be [13, -1, 1].
Finally, bubbles [13, -1, 1] and [5, 3, 4] are chosen as the first and second bubbles respectively. The new bubble formed after merging these two bubbles will be [18, -4, -3].
The last bubble has coordinates (-4, -3) which is the required answer.

textdisplay: Hi, man. Your videos are very helpful, thank you for doing this. I'm reading the book "Cracking the coding (green one)" and there is on page 45 it says that tree's time complexity is O(branches^depth) which in this case gives us O(2^n). Can you please explain or refer me to why it's O(n) in your video?

author: @lukealexanderhwilson
textdisplay:
Consider how the tree changes when you add a number to the root. Any number can be added to extend the tree by one. Let's say we add a node at the top with a value of 1, now the summation will run the exact same way, but then tunnel upward one more level to the root value 1. There is one more computation done. Thus O(n) time complexity.

However in other situations, when you add a value to the tree it by design propagates outward. It creates an entire duplicate tree underneath it. An example is the Fibonacci sequence. Adding a value at the top means mirroring the entire tree underneath. This is O(2^n)

Searching a tree that exists is O(n), but an algorithm that builds a tree with # of leafs branching outward from each node in the chain is O(#^n).

# This is code for rotated array. First we define function for rotate array in particular direction then we give input that rotated array in Binary search code.
# If the code will help you please like the comment.
def rotate_ntime(arr,direction, n):
if direction=="Left":
for i in range(n):
left_rotate_one(arr)
if direction=="Right":
for i in range(n):
right_rotate_one(arr)

return arr

def left_rotate_one(arr):
temp=arr[0]
for i in range(len(arr)-1):
arr[i]=arr[i+1]
arr[len(arr)-1]=temp
return arr
def right_rotate_one(arr):
temp=arr[len(arr)-1]
for i in range(len(arr)-1,0,-1):
arr[i]=arr[i-1]
arr[0]=temp
return arr

arr=[8,9,11,13,-2,3,4,7]
arr=rotate_ntime(arr,"Left",4)
print(arr)

def Binary_search(arr,target):
low=0
high=len(arr)-1
while low<=high:
mid = (low + high) // 2
if arr[mid]==target:
return mid
elif arr[mid]<target:
low=mid+1
else:
high=mid-1

print(Binary_search(arr,11))

author: @igor_cojocaru
textdisplay:
Thank you! Sharing my JS implementation:

const quickSort = (arr, l, r) => {
if (l >= r) {
return;
}

const p = partition(arr, l, r);

quickSort(arr, l, p - 1);
quickSort(arr, p + 1, r);
};

const partition = (arr, l, r) => {
const pivot = arr[r];

let i = l - 1;

for (let j = l; j < r; j++) {
if (arr[j] < pivot) {
i += 1;
[arr[i], arr[j]] = [arr[j], arr[i]];
}
}

[arr[i + 1], arr[r]] = [arr[r], arr[i + 1]];

return i + 1;
};

author: @nikhilnayak2179
textdisplay:
solution in python

class Stack:
def __init__(self):
self.items = []

def isEmpty(self):
return self.items == []

def push(self, item):
self.items.append(item)

def pop(self):
return self.items.pop()

def peek(self):
return self.items[len(self.items)-1]

def size(self):
return len(self.items)

def parChecker(symbolString):
s = Stack()
balanced = True
index = 0
while index < len(symbolString) and balanced:
symbol = symbolString[index]
if symbol in "([{":
s.push(symbol)
else:
if s.isEmpty():
balanced = False
else:
top = s.pop()
if not matches(top,symbol):
balanced = False
index = index + 1
if balanced and s.isEmpty():
return True
else:
return False

def matches(open,close):
opens = "([{"
closers = ")]}"
return opens.index(open) == closers.index(close)


print(parChecker('{({([][])}())}'))
print(parChecker('[{()]'))

def convert(type, distance):
if(type == "km"):
km = distance * 1.609344
return float(km)
elif(type == "miles"):
miles = distance / 1.609344;
return float(miles)
else:
return distance


mileToKm = convert("km", 2);
print(mileToKm)

kmtoMiles = convert("miles", 1)
print(kmtoMiles)

author: @tayyabullah9260
textdisplay:
I've a question:

Why do we need a return statement after all?

My ambiguity:
I'm asking this because we can use the print() function instead of the "return" statement and call our function without printing it. If we do this, we don't get a "None" return value either, so why do we use a return statement at all?

More explanation: I know if we don't use the "return statement" and print our function when we call it, we get a 'None' return value, but that's useless to me, as I'm not sure why we do that. I've experimented that we don't need to "print" our function when we call it to get the "return value", instead, we can simply replace the "return" statement with "print()" and then call our function, without printing it. With this approach, we don't get the 'None' return value either.

textdisplay:
Hello! can someone help me with this code please? I'm having trouble with it:
def create_dictionary_from_csv(filename, separator):
data_dict = {}

with open(filename, 'r') as file:
lines = file.readlines()

if len(lines) < 2:
return data_dict

keys = lines[0].strip().split(separator)

for line in lines[1:]:
values = line.strip().split(separator)

if len(values) != len(keys):
continue

row_dict = {key: value for key, value in zip(keys, values)}
data_dict.update(row_dict)

return data_dict

author: @Artdeto
textdisplay:
Maybe this will help someone understand 3:10 . It took me a long time to figure out.

We can divide the code in 2 parts:
# 1 - Outside Loop
for i in range(len(a)):
# 2 - Inside Loop
for j in range(i + 1)
print(a[i])



Outside loop based on range(3) means there are 3 items in the range (0, 1, 2) and the code inside the loop will run for each item in the range:
for 0
run Inside loop
for 1
run Inside loop
for 2
run Inside loop



Now figure out the inside loop for each element of the Outside loop. Remember j is just the variable that denotes each item in the range. It's not about calculating the value of j but how many js there will be. How many js there will be is given by the range(i + 1).


- range for i = 0 -> i + 1 = 1, range(1) means the inside loop will run only once because there is only one item in the range, this item has a value of 0. The value 0 itself doesn't matter because it still counts as one item.
- range for i = 1 -> i + 1 = 2, range(2) means the inside loop will run twice because there are 2 items in this range, these items are 0 and 1
- range for i = 2 -> i + 1 = 3, range(3) means the inside loop will run three times because there are 3 items in this range, these items are 0, 1 and 2

Why do we put minus 1 when we use

author: @swallowedinthesea11
textdisplay:
Because the last item is always the length minus 1.

x = [5, 7, 9, 0, 3] # length is 5

x[0] # item is 5 because counting lists begin at zero.
x[4] # item is 3, the last item
j = len(x) - 1 # length of x is 5. 5 - 1 is 4
print( x[j] ) # x[4] is 3, the last item

You could also use:
x[-1] # -1 will always get the last item
x[-2] # -2 will get 0
x[-3] # -3 will get 9
x[-4] # -4 will get 7
x[-5] # -5 will get 5

author: @swallowedinthesea11
textdisplay:
If the variables are all common along with the values being common too, you can write a dictionary instead of writing each variable on each new line.

Dictionary:

rating = {
'Anita Sarkeesian': 9,
'Belle Delphine': 10,
'Kim Kardashian': 8,
}

Variables:

anitaSarkeesian = 9
belleDelphine = 10
kimKardashian = 8

Experienced programmers wouldn't do the variable way because a dictionary is more convenient when you want to pair keys and values together.

This is the same reason why lists are used instead of variables when you want to group common values together:

List:

grocery = [ 'apples', 'chocolate', 'sushi', 'wasabi' ]

Variables:

grocery = 'apples'
grocery2 = 'chocolate'
grocery3 = 'sushi'
grocery4 = 'wasabi'

Imagine that you were assigned to make a database of the top 100 most irrelevant influencers in the world. Writing each variable and the rating line by line would be hard for the eyes and add a lot of 'noise' to your program.

author: @dylanf7990
textdisplay:
"is" should never be used this way, it is to test object identity, basically whether two things refer to the same address in memory. You would need to change "is" to "==", however this still would not work because comparison operators are non associative, you would need to add brackets like this "if (c>d+e) == True:" but since the if statement is already checking whether the operation is True, you don't need to compare whether it is True a second time, so you can simply shorten the code to

def c_greater_than_d_plus_e(c, d, e):
if c > d + e:
return True
else:
return False

author: @felixb8418
textdisplay:
Why pick SENG over CS:
1) In Canada the word "engineer" is reserved and some industries require projects to be signed by engineers.
2) Engineers make significantly more money (on average 10-15k/year more than CS).
3) Better hire rate after degree completion.
4) You have a lot more general knowledge of business and project management.
5) Safer job prosperity, with AI code-generating tools, knowing how to design is valuable.

Why pick CS over SENG:
1) It's an easier degree.
2) You take programming courses earlier in your degree which helps with co-op internships.
3) You can boost your gpa by picking easier electives.
4) Degree can be done in 3 years vs 4-5 years for SENG.
5) CS degree is cheaper than SENG.

In general, in terms of courses, SENG and CS have an identical foundation. Most SENG students have as many CS-electives than CS students. The difference is that CS doesn't require you to do electrical and computer engineering courses as well as other design courses.

For me, I am studying SENG and I also don't recommend it. It's way too much effort and it isn't rewarding. I'm in too deep now anyways. 1.5 more years and I am done!

author: @redbeardhomes
textdisplay:
def decode(char):
intVal = int(char) # 97 is for a but a =
if intVal>0 and intVal <=26: # that means that the char is vali
return 0
return -1

def decodeNumWays(string):
prevChar = None
numWays = 0
for char in string:
base = decode(char)
if base != -1:
if prevChar != None and prevChar != '0':
concat = prevChar+char
converted = decode(concat)
if converted != -1:
numWays = numWays * 2
elif numWays == 0:
numWays = 1
prevChar = char

return numWays

author: @pbike5118
textdisplay: Actually, I find third solution - in my opinion more efficient -  so I will post it there. The only possibility to occure part which can be decoded in 2 ways (ex "12")  is when we have 1 or 2 in the str . So if the program see "1" automatically it will ad up 1 to the counter. And if it sees the 2 and the next digit is at most 6 it will add one ass well. The counter represenst here the anount of pairs which can be translated in two ways. Therefore the final answerr will be just 2 rised to the counter. EX. for "7432481312" ans is 8 (2**3) bcs. we have only three such pairs: "24" , "13" , "12".

author: @yarinl33
textdisplay:
This is my solution O(n) without recursion:

def num_ways(text):
prev_counter, counter = 0, 1
for i, v in enumerate(text):
temp = counter
if i == 0 and v == '0':
return 0
if v == '0':
if text[i-1] not in ['1', '2']:
return 0
counter = 0
if 10 <= int(text[i-1] + v) <= 26:
counter += prev_counter
prev_counter = temp
return counter

author: @deanroddey2881
textdisplay: A simple iteration through the string would work fine, and be the lightest weight way possible probably. Check the empty and 0 first character bits. If not, then call a helper with start and end indices or iterators. Then it just loops. On each round, while it still has input, it knows one character is always good, so add 1 to return. If there's another available, it looks at the value of the first one. If it's 1, then the next character has to be valid. If it's 2, then the next character is valid if less than 7. So in those cases move up and add another 1 to the return. Now you are on the next character and just repeat until out of data. On each round you add 1 or 2 to the return value and move up 1 or 2 positions. At the end, return the accumulated count.

author: @ajalbani
textdisplay:
excellent.. Here is the JS version of it.. with simplified code
```
let memo = {};
const num_ways = (str) => {
if(memo[str]) return memo[str];
const isAlpha = (str2) => {
let n = parseInt(str2, 10);
return n > 9 && n < 27;
}
if(str.length === 0) return 1;
memo[str] = num_ways(str.substr(1)) + (isAlpha(str.substr(0,2)) ? num_ways(str.substr(2)) : 0);
return memo[str];
}
console.log('ways', num_ways("1127"));
```

author: @productivityexpert
textdisplay:
Summary: See the problem as a Fibonacci Sequence with j initial conditions.

Solutions:
1) used recursion to solve the problem [problem? not time efficient]
2) improved time complexity with DP (dynamic programming) [problem? space complexity]
3) improved space complexity by reducing the size of the array 'nums' from N+1 to j because we need only previous j values at each iteration

KEYS:
[N] = total steps in the ladder
[j] = size of the array contains different steps i.e {1,3,5} in this case
[nums] = array used to store num of ways to reach a particular step [value at ith index represents a different number of ways to reach ith step] used this array to improve the time complexity

thanks for the video, I had not found a comment in the comment section that states there is a bug in your code, for the X set of possible jumps (I confess I did not look through too many comments :))
The bug is that you assume that all steps are reachable to begin with and that is true if you assume that 1 is always part of the set X, but in the general case, where X can be any int array (not containing 1 for example) you need to skip those unreachable steps in the for loop, you can either do that with another reachable bool array (that you init only the first step with true) or init your nums array to -1 to all the values apart from nums[0] and in the for loop verify the value you are about to update is not negative.

author: @brianjenkins7647
textdisplay:
for the first problem I looked at what happens with 8:

8 = 2+2+2+2 4C4 = 1
8 = 2+2+2+1+1 5C3 = 10
8 = 2+2+1+1+1+1 6C2 = 15
8 = 2+1+1+1+1+1+1 7C1 = 7
8 = 1+1+1+1+1+1+1+1 8C0 = 1

so it would be the sum [(r + i) C (k - i), for i in 0:k], where r = shortest chain length = int(n/2) + (n % 2) = k + (n % 2)

so you're increasing the length of each chain by 1, and youre counting the number of ways to place a 2 in each chain. The sum of all these combos gives the answer, which as shown in the video, is also the nth fibbonaci number.

author: @MrRichiban
textdisplay:
When presented with a problem like this it's always a good idea to abstract their analogies away from the problem; i.e.reduce it to pure maths.

In this case you'd say "So basically this is asking me how many ways I can make a list consisting of 1s and 2s (or whatever) that sums to 4".

When you reduce the problem like this you realise "Hang on, this is the same as asking how many different ways there are to make change given certain coins, and that I have solved before".

It's as much about identifying the class of problem as coming up with a solution on the spot.

author: @4th3PPL
textdisplay:
This morning, I remembered this video and decided to try the problem in Python. However, I included an additional if statement to account for an empty list. Feel free to let me know if it could have been done better.

def add_one(numbers):

zeros = []
loop_again = True

#keep looping if loop_again == True
while loop_again:

#if numbers[] is empty
if numbers == []:
#an empty list was given to the function
if zeros == []:
return numbers

#only 9's were provided in numbers[]
else:
zeros.insert(0, 1) #carries the 1 from the final 0
numbers = zeros
loop_again = False

#if the last element in numbers[] is 9
elif numbers[-1] == 9:
del numbers[-1] #delete the element
zeros.append(0) #and add one zero to zeros[]

#if the last element in numbers[] is not 9
else:
numbers[-1] = numbers[-1] + 1 #add 1 to the last element
numbers = numbers + zeros #and add any 0's, from carrying the 1, to the end of the list
loop_again = False

return numbers #return the list + 1

public class Abhi {

public static int[] fun(int[] arr) {

int len = arr.length;
int carry = 1;

if((arr[len-1] + 1)/10==0)
{
arr[len-1] = arr[len-1] + 1;
return arr;
}

int[] arr1 = new int[len];

for(int i=len-1;i>=0;i--) {
arr1[i] = (arr[i] + carry)%10;
carry = (arr[i] + 1)/10;
}

if(carry==0) {
return arr1;
}

int[] arr2 = new int[len+1];

for(int i=len;i>=1;i--) {
arr2[i] =arr1[i-1];
}
arr2[0] = carry;

return arr2;
}

public static void main(String[] args)
{
int[] arr = {1,3,4};
int[] result = fun(arr);

for(int i=0;i<result.length;i++) {
System.out.print(result[i]+" ");
}
}
}

for x in range(len(n)):
sum = abs(n[x][0]) + abs(n[x][1])
store.append([n[x], sum])

for x in range(len(n)):

find_lowest = True
current = x
while find_lowest:

if current != 0 and store[current][1] < store[current - 1][1]:
store[current], store[current - 1] = store[current - 1], store[current]

current -= 1

else:
find_lowest = False

for num in range(k):
new_store.append(store[num][0])

return new_store

This is my solution:
import math, sys

class Node:
def __init__(self, name, left, right):
self.name = name
self.left = left
self.right = right

def kclosest(p):
n = Node((sys.maxsize-2, 0, 0), (sys.maxsize-1, 0, 0), (sys.maxsize,0,0))
for i in p:
dist = math.sqrt(math.pow(i[0],2) + math.pow(i[1],2))
if n.right[0] > dist:
tmp_1 = n.name
tmp_2 = n.left
n.left = tmp_1
n.right = tmp_2
n.name = dist , i[0], i[1]
return n

author: @tonytoeknee3192
textdisplay: Why does adding the runtimes all up result in O( n+(n-k)log(k)) time?

author: @BraedenSmith
textdisplay: It doesn't, that runtime is incorrect, it should be O(nlogk) -- everything else gets dropped.

author: @tonytoeknee3192
textdisplay: @@BraedenSmith can you explain why?

author: @BraedenSmith
textdisplay:
@@tonytoeknee3192 since big O is an asymptomatic notation. In English O(f) for some function f means the thing we're describing grows asymptotically no faster than f.

So if we're trying to describe G=x^5+28488x^4+x+99999 the big O notation of this can be written as O(x^10000) since that is a valid upper bound, but in standard notation, it's O(x^5) since we drop all smaller terms and constants.

So for this runtime, since nlog(k) >> n as n and k approach infinity. O(n+nlog(k)) is written as O(nlog(k)) since the n term is negligible in big O. And as for the n-k, since k is strictly less then n, it can be written as n.


Hopefully that makes sense, I'd advise you to check out:
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_O_notation

author: @rafaelocariz1384
textdisplay:
another solution is to use a binary tree and an inorder traversal until you find the k elements you want. I believe this will give you an O(N log N + k) complexity. Also, you don't need the sqrt task.
Explaining the complexity to those who didn't understand: O(N log N + k)
- N log N: the algorithm will need to look over all the points coordinates on the given array (N) and insert them into the tree (log N)
- k: the inorder traversal returns the data already ordered, so you just need a k amount of elements, you don't need to complete the traversal, this is why k.

With this approach, you reduce all the time loosed balancing a max-heap tree on almost every insertion.

I'm not saying it's a better solution, but it's another approach with excellent performance.

function findClosest(closestPoints, points)
{
var closest = [];
for(var i=0; i<points.length; i++)
{
var total = Math.abs(points[i][0]) + Math.abs(points[i][1]);
closest.push({"points": points[i], "total": total});
}
closest.sort(function(a,b) {return a.total - b.total;});
return closest.slice(0, closestPoints);
}

author: @saurabhtripathi5929
textdisplay:
class Solution {
public int[][] kClosest(int[][] points, int K) {
PriorityQueue<Point> pq = new PriorityQueue<Point>(10000,new Mycomp());

// Adding points into priority queue will create min heap based on distance since class implements comparator
for(int i=0;i<points.length;i++){
Point p = new Point(points[i][0],points[i][1]);
pq.add(p);
}

// Find k points from priority queue. Those k will be having minimum distance an put into output array
int c = 0;
int res[][] = new int[K][2];
while(c < K){
Point q = pq.poll();
res[c][0] = q.x;
res[c][1] = q.y;
c++;
}

return res;
}
}

class Point
{
int x;
int y;
Point (int x,int y)
{
this.x =x;
this.y =y;
}
}

class Mycomp implements Comparator<Point>{
public int compare(Point a,Point b){
double dista = Math.pow(a.x,2) + Math.pow (a.y,2);
double distb = Math.pow(b.x,2) + Math.pow (b.y,2);
if (distb > dista){
return -1;
}
else
{
return 1;
}
}
}

author: @ACarbonellBeceiro
textdisplay:
You don't loop, but query it directly with a given key, in this case the char itself.

Example: hashTable.has('A') // true or false if the table has that key
or: hashTable.get('A') != null // true or false if the table has that key

I did show 2 variations because it can vary from one language to another. The .has() method is just a helper that some implementations offer. The second example can cause problems if we actually want to store null values, but for this case works fine.

A hashtable has a constant access time, O(1), so the overall time complexity does not increment.

textdisplay:
Yes you can.
1) Binary search the first row for first negative
2) Then go down. That position becomes the maximum for the next binary search
3) and so on

It's still O(C) because you might visit every cell worse case but it would be logC for the average. Where C is the number of columns. Kinda like how quicksort is O(N^2) but averages at NlogN.

So log would be more optional just not for the worst case.

You could also do two binary searches one from the bottom row and one from the top and trim the min/max as you meet in the middle.

textdisplay:
Let's take a real life example for when finding subsets can be useful. Imagine, you are creating an online restaurant where people can order food and have it delivered. We have a smoothie section in our menu and we want to give the options to customers to pick from available fruits. They have a set of fruits to pick from. Based on the choice of the customer, the app should be able to display the calorie information and display the preset price.

For example,

Smoothie fruits = {apple, banana, kiwi}

In this context, we have to derive the possible combinations that the customer will choose and decide on the price and calories for that mix.
‚Ä¢ The customer can choose to not have any smoothie. That is encapsulated with an empty subset {}
‚Ä¢ The following are the possible other combinations
‚óã {apple}
‚óã {banana}
‚óã {kiwi}
‚óã {apple, banana}
‚óã {apple, kiwi}
‚óã {banana, kiwi}
‚óã {apple, banana, kiwi}

Now that we have all available subsets, we can preset the information for the combination(price, name, calorific info) and greatly improve the customer experience!

author: @Shini1984
textdisplay:
Thanks for visualizing the recursion tree, it gave me an idea how to solve this, but I couldn't put it into words till I finished watching the video.
I've made an iterative solution using Javascript. At each step, it makes a decision whether to add an item to current combination or not. This significantly simplified the code I was trying to write, thanks for all the tips! Code:
function powerSet(inputs) {
const results = [];
const stack = [[[], 0]];

while(stack.length > 0) {
const [combination, index] = stack.pop();
// we have reached the final index of combination, push to results and exit
if (index === inputs.length) {
results.push(combination);
continue;
}
// do not add current element, make a copy of existing combination and push it to stack
stack.push([[...combination], index + 1]);

// add current element to combination and push it to stack
combination.push(inputs[index]);
stack.push([combination, index + 1]);
}

return results;
};

package problems;


import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;


public class SubsetFinder {
public static void main(String[] args) {
int[] input = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6};
Node root = new Node();
for(int i=0; i<input.length; i++) {
insertIntoTree(root, input[i]);
}
printLeafNodes(root);
}

static void printLeafNodes(Node root) {

if(root == null) {
return;
}

// Its a leaf node
if(root.left == null && root.right == null) {
System.out.println(root.values);
return;
}

if(root.left !=null) {
printLeafNodes(root.left);
}

if(root.right != null) {
printLeafNodes(root.right);
}
}

static void insertIntoTree(Node root, int value) {
if(root == null) {
return;
}

if(root.left !=null && root.right != null) {
insertIntoTree(root.left, value);
insertIntoTree(root.right, value);
return;
}

if(root.left == null && root.right == null) {
root.left = new Node();
root.left.values.addAll(root.values);

root.right = new Node();
root.right.values.addAll(root.values);
root.right.values.add(value);
return;
}
}


}


class Node {
Node left;
Node right;
List<Integer> values = new ArrayList<Integer>();
}

author: @gnagyusa
textdisplay:
Your solution is very inefficient. It's much faster and easier to follow the path the other way around. From lower nodes, toward the root, via "parent" links. This guarantees a straight path every time, without having to split off into branches.
It will also give you the LCA almost for free: as you traverse up from each node, all you have to do is to stop at the first node that matches. This will be the LCA.

author: @kevinmartin7760
textdisplay:
The problem is ill-defined. You seem to be assuming that the nodes have left and right properties but this is not stated anywhere in the problem definition.
If we can assume whatever properties might ordinarily exist in tree nodes for our solution, I would assume we have depth and parent properties. The solution is then much simpler: On the node with more depth, follow the parent chain until it is the same depth as the other node. Then follow the parent chains of both nodes until you find the common parent.
If you have no depth property but you have parent you can calculate the depths yourself and figure out how many parent references to follow to make the depths match.

author: @KosovoJeSrceSrbije89
textdisplay: This can't be an optimal solution you go over the same elements two times, and you don't really need to use so much space.. You should findPathToXorY, then when you find one of those elements, put that element as the current goalParent, and continue the search for the element you didn't find(X or Y). Every time you go up in the tree( from a child to it's parent) put that element as the current goalParent of the solution, as soon as you find the other element, return the current goalParent. This solution has the same time complexity( it's better by a constant) and the space complexity is better( O(1) ).

author: @marcorossetti4484
textdisplay:
Here is a solution (python code), probably not the most efficient one, hope it helps.

lst = [1, -4, 5, 6, -2] # example input

def find_maxsublist(lst):
"""Only lst with global maximum needed (even if weak maximum, i.e. other sublists with same max sum, shorter len not taken into account). Only lists of consecutive elements are valid."""
l = lst.copy()
lstmax = [l[0]] # initialise list with maximum sum as first element
max_sum = sum(lstmax)
for n_e in range(len(l)): # n_e --> number of the element
start = n_e+1
for end in range(start, len(l)+1):
match = l[n_e:end] # all sublists (of consecutives) become, at some point, a match
match_sum = sum(match) # compute match sum
if match_sum > max_sum: # we only care if better than max, if so: set new max
max_sum = match_sum
lstmax = match
return lstmax, max_sum

print(find_maxsublist(lst)) # outputs ([5, 6), 11) for the lst given

author: @JustWatchingVideo56
textdisplay:
Actually that is O(n*log(n)). This is the proof:

T(n) = 2*T(n/2) + n
T(n) = 2*(2*T(n/4) + n/2) + n
T(n) = 4*T(n/4) + n + n
T(n) = 4*T(n/4) + 2*n

In general, if you continue this k times, then you would see that it would end up like this:
T(n) = (2^k)*T(n/(2^k)) + k*n

Then you must apply a base case such as T(1) = O(1). (I'm not sure what else you can make this but it could up becoming an exponentially growing problem, which is very bad)
So to get to the base case the term inside T(n/(2^k)) must equal to 1. And

n/(2^k) = 1
n = 2^k
log_2(n) = k*log_2(2)
log_2(n) = k

Then you apply this to the original T(n) function and replace T(n/(2^k)) with T(1) because that was where we wanted to end up based on our last condition we applied.

T(n) = 2^[log_2(n)] * T(1) + log_2(n) * n
T(n) = n*T(1) + n*log_2(n)

Since we know T(1) = O(1) as the base case we can do:

T(n) = n * O(1) + n*log_2(n)

You can see here n*log_2(n) is the dominating term thus it would follow that:

T(n) = O(n*log_2(n))

In general, O(f(n)) = c*f(n). Most times you would see that people drop the base and make it O(n*log(n)) because it can be factored into the constant like so:

O(log_2(n)) = c*log_2(n) = c * (1/log(2)) * log(n) = C * log(n) = O(log(n))

#include <random>
#include <time.h>


int Rand(int min, int max)
{
if (max - min == 0) return 0;
return rand() % (max - min) + min;
}


template<class T>
void RandomReorder(T arr[], int size)
{
srand(time(0)):
for (int i = 0; i < size; ++i)
{
int swapIndex = Rand(0, size - 1);
T temp = arr[i];
arr[i] = arr[swapIndex];
arr[swapIndex] = temp;
}


}

author: @noamzilo6730
textdisplay:
this solution lacks the very important PROOF that the probability for any number to land at any index is the same, so here it is:
calculation for the probability for some index i to land in index 0:
1/n, as it is the 1st iteration.
calculation for the probability for some index i to land in index 1:
(n-1)/n * (1/(n-1)). the left hand side is the probability for index j!=i to be selected, because i is already selected, and can't be selected again.
the selection from (n-1) index has probability of (1/(n-1)).
Now apply same logic for array of size k=n-1, for any k.
stopping condition: n=1 (or 0), for probability 1 to land in index 0.

Python code:

def swap(arr, i, j):
assert i < len(arr)
assert j < len(arr)
temp = arr[i]
arr[i] = arr[j]
arr[j] = temp

def reorder_in_place(arr):
length = len(arr)
for i in range(length):
dice = random.randrange(i, length)
swap(arr, i, dice)
return arr

author: @SirSethery
textdisplay:
I have a problem with that method in that it isn't random.
If it were truly random, the last number would have just as high of a chance of remaining as the last number as any other number would have a chance of replacing it.
The solution I had was similar, but you could switch with either the left or the right side of the current number. You could pick a random number from the left side and from the right side and pick one of those two to switch, weighing the odds by how many numbers were on each side. If you wanted, you could repeat the whole thing a few times to make it more random, and it would remain O(n).

Edit
Actually, it may be easier to simply do this method from right to left and then repeat it from left to right while still being random *enough*

author: @wulymammoth
textdisplay:
There is a lot of confusion here. I believe what you were going for is the modern Fisher-Yates shuffle algorithm. Anybody interested can look it up on Wikipedia.

The modern FY states that when you first start from right to left at n-1, 0 <= j <= i. That is ‚Äî j should be between indices 0 and i (inclusive).

I looked very carefully at this on Wikipedia. What that means is that the value/position at n-1 should be considered. The range decreases as we decrement i, but the current position at i should remain in consideration. I believe this is the only error.

author: @wulymammoth
textdisplay: @@ZantierTasa if you look at 4:58, you'll see that the range is 0 <= 4 * rand() < 4. the last index in a five-element zero-based index array is 4. "< 4" indicates that this is not inclusive of the last index (the algorithm states that it should be). must be very careful with off-by-one errors when it comes to indexing into arrays. the shuffle may "work", but not as intended as it does not adhere to the algorithm. similarly, a lot of academic texts and their implementations of binary search contain an error very similar to this because of the incorrect comparison operator.

My solution in JS before watching the video:

function interval_int_rand(low, high) {
return Math.floor(Math.random() * (high - low) + low)
}

function rearrange(array) {
const result = [...array];
for (let i = 0; i < result.length; i++) {
const index = interval_int_rand(i, result.length);
const temp = result[i];

result[i] = result[index];
result[index] = temp;
}
return result;
}

def findConsecutive(set):
counts = {}
prevChar = None
for i in set:
if i in counts:
if i == prevChar:
prevChar = i
counts[i] += 1
else:
prevChar = i
counts[i] = 1
else:
prevChar = i
counts[i] = 1
return max(counts, key=counts.get)

def LCC_error(string):
hashmap = {}
count = 0
char = ''
hashmap[string[0:1]] = 1
for i in range(1, len(string)):
if (char in hashmap) & (string[i:i+1] == char):
v = hashmap[string[i:i + 1]]
hashmap[string[i:i+1]] = v + 1
else:
if char == string[i:i+1]:
count = count + 1

hashmap[char] = count

textdisplay:
It is better to return an object with two keys: one for the length of the longest run, and one for the letter that compose the longest run.

I wrote my solution in javascript:

function longestRun(s) {
let max = {letter:'',run:0};
let current = {letter:'',run:0};
for (let i = 0; i <= s.length; i++) {
if (current.letter !== s[i]) {
if (current.run > max.run) {
max.letter = current.letter;
max.run = current.run;
}
current.run = 0;
current.letter = s[i];
}
current.run++;
}
return max;
}

author: @RealMcDudu
textdisplay:
You don't really have to hold the previous char and the current char. You could do it a bit differently, starting on the 2nd character and continuing counting until you reach a different char, then updating the counters. Also, if you can, it's better to return a simple tuple and not a hash table, as you're not really using the hashtables functionalities... C# syntax follows:

static Tuple<char,int> FindLongestConsecutiveChar(string s)
{
if(String.IsNullOrEmpty(s))
return null;
char maxChar = s[0];
int maxCount = 1;
int currentCount = 1;
for (int i = 1; i < s.Length; i++)
{
if (s[i] == s[i - 1])
currentCount++;
else
{
if(currentCount > maxCount)
{
maxChar = s[i - 1];
maxCount = currentCount;
currentCount = 1;
}
}
}
return new Tuple<char, int> (maxChar, maxCount);
}

textdisplay:
Keep track of the currentStep, each iteration decrease this currentStep, and check if current index + currentStep is >= arr length then return true. Then check if currentStep = 0: we update currentStep with the step at current index, or if arr[i] > currentStep we will update the currentStep with arr[i] (cause at this point arr[i] is the largest step). Finally when out the loop, which means we have iterate through the whole array, just need to check if currentStep is > 0

int currentStep = arr[0];
for (int i = 1; i < arr.length; ++i) {
--currentStep;
if (i + currentStep >= arr.length) {
return true;
}
if (arr[i] > currentStep || currentStep == 0) {
currentStep = arr[i];
}
}
return currentStep > 0;

Here is my recursive solution in java:
public static boolean isHoppable(int[] towers){
if (towers[0] >= towers.length) {return true;} // checks if you can jump to end from the start
for (int i = towers.length-1; i > 0; i--) {
if (towers[i] >= towers.length-i){
return isHoppable(Arrays.copyOfRange(towers,0,i)); // cuts off the array at every point that lets you exit the array. And then calls this function on that array.
}
}
return false;
}

My Solution:

def tower_hopping(towers, index = 0):
hops = towers[index]
if index+hops >= len(towers):
return True
for i in range(hops):
if tower_hopping(towers, index+hops-i) == True:
return True
return False


Having the default value of index equal to 0, saves the need of another function, which calls the function for the first time.
Basically the function travels to every reachable tower and as soon as he reaches an index beyond the array he returns true
If he reaches a 0, he won't go into the for loop and returns False

Simple O(n) python solution. We only need a way to skip each "dead zone". Traversing once from the end will be enough:

def is_hoppable(towers):
dead_zone = 0
for tower in towers[::-1]:
if tower > dead_zone:
dead_zone = 0
else:
dead_zone += 1
return dead_zone == 0

author: @yoramtsv
textdisplay:
A short & elegant O(n) solution:
def is_hoppable(towers):
n = 1
for k in towers:
n = max(n-1,k)
if n==0:
return False
return True


The idea, looking this as a game with "life" -
* As long as n>0 you have life, otherwise you're dead.
* Any step decrease your life by 1.
* A bitter tower refills your life.

author: @iancuvlad7368
textdisplay:
I have a solution that is even more simple and runs in complexity of O(n)
1.We start from the end of the array and we look for the closest tower (in the left).
2.We repeat step 1 with the tower we found in the step before (instead of the end).
3.If we have a tower located at a position k in the array (from which we know we can reach the end) and there
is no tower in its left from we can jump to k, we return false.
4.If the algorithm has reached the first tower in the array (without encountering step 3) then the tower is
hoppable so we return true.
The full code is in the following gist:
https://gist.github.com/2000Vlad/5449fb23cf3c05c2f05e5e1ef3d5dbd2

textdisplay: from index 0, the furthest we can go is index 2. From index 0 to 2, we have 3 options for next jump 0->2, 1->1, 2->5. So the optimal is 2->5. So we go to index 2. At index 2, the furthest we can go is 5. From index 2 to 5, we have 4 options for the next jump 2->5, 3->3, 4->out, 5->5 . So the optimal is 4->out. So we go to index 4. At index 4, the furthest we can go is above the max index, so we return true.

function isHopable(towers, startIndex)
{
var isHop = false;
var steps = towers[startIndex];

//base condition
if(steps === 0) return isHop;

for(var i=startIndex+1; i<=startIndex + steps; i++)
{
if(towers[i + towers[i]] === undefined)
{
return true;
}
else if(towers[i] > 0)
{
isHop = isHopable(towers, i);
}
}
return isHop;

here is the simplest solution using recursion , only 8 lines of code

bool hopable(int*ar,int b,int len){

//base case
if(ar[b]>=len-b){
return true;
}

//recursive case
int distance=ar[b];

for(int i=b+1;i<=b+distance;i++){
if(ar[i]>0){
if(hopable(ar,i,len)){
return true;
}
}
}
return false;
}

textdisplay:
let array = [2,4,6,10]

let value = 16;



add(0, 0, "")



function add(num, index, current){

if(index == array.length) return;
if(num == value) return console.log(current);
if(num + array[index] == value) return console.log(current);

add(num + array[index], index+1, current+":"+array[index] )
add(num, index+1, current);

}

author: @rafaeldiaz4530
textdisplay:
I think I have a shorter solution?

def rec (arr, total, i) {
if total == 0 return 1;
if i == 0 return (arr[i] == total) ? 1 : 0;
return rec(arr, total - arr[i], i - 1) + rec(arr, total, i - 1);
}

author: @tanaykulkarni2116
textdisplay:
Please try this

Supervin loves to eat candies. Today, his favorite candy shop is offering N candies, which are arranged in a line. The i-th candy in the line (counting starting from 1) has a sweetness level Si. Note that the sweetness level of a candy might be negative, which means the candy tastes bitter.

Supervin likes to eat sweet candies. However, candies with a combined sweetness level of more than D would be too much sweetness even for him. Supervin also realises that a candy with an odd sweetness level is "odd", and he does not want to eat more than O odd candies. In other words, an odd candy is a candy with a sweetness level that is not evenly divisible by 2. Additionally, since Supervin is in a rush, he can only eat a single contiguous subset of candies.

Therefore, he wants to eat a contiguous non-empty subset of candies in which there are at most O odd candies and the total sweetness level is maximized, but not more than D. Help Supervin to determine the maximum total sweetness level he can get, or return IMPOSSIBLE if there is no contiguous subset satisfying these constraints.

author: @nikhilgumidelli6308
textdisplay:
For this who did not understand the bottom-up solution :

The bottom up approach is similar to the recursive solution

we start from n=0, m=0 . The first row and the first column will be 0. From n=1, m=1 we follow this :
if P[n] == Q[m] :
lcs[n,m] = 1 + lcs[n-1, m-1]
else :
lcs[n,m] = max(lcs[n-1, m] , lcs[n, m-1])

The thinking behind this is the same as the recursive solution but we are just starting from the first and does not involve multiple function calls on the stack. Hope this makes it clear.

var longLen = arr1.length > arr2.length ? arr1.length : arr2.length;

//cache long string characters
for(var j=0; j<longLen; j++)
{
var lChar = arr1.length > arr2.length ? arr1[j] : arr2[j];
obj[lChar] = 0;
}

for(var i=0; i<shortLen; i++)
{
var sChar = arr1.length < arr2.length ? arr1[i] : arr2[i];
if(obj[sChar] === 0)
{
string += sChar;
obj[sChar]++;
}
}
return string;
}

textdisplay: Does memoization optimization of the recursive function really help for this problem? I mean, if you take the example in the video, the keys for each recursive call in preorder are the following for a zero-based array: 3:6, 2:-4, 2:6, 1:0, 1:6, 0:2, -1:0, -1:2,  0:6, -1:4, -1:6. There are no identical keys, so, at least with these values, memoization is useless. I suppose memoization would not increase efficiency with other values as well. The dynamic programming way to go, at least for this problem, is the tabulation method in my opinion.

I think I have a shorter solution?

def rec (arr, total, i) {
if total == 0 return 1;
if i == 0 return (arr[i] == total) ? 1 : 0;
return rec(arr, total - arr[i], i - 1) + rec(arr, total, i - 1);
}

author: @tanaykulkarni2116
textdisplay:
Please try this

Supervin loves to eat candies. Today, his favorite candy shop is offering N candies, which are arranged in a line. The i-th candy in the line (counting starting from 1) has a sweetness level Si. Note that the sweetness level of a candy might be negative, which means the candy tastes bitter.

Supervin likes to eat sweet candies. However, candies with a combined sweetness level of more than D would be too much sweetness even for him. Supervin also realises that a candy with an odd sweetness level is "odd", and he does not want to eat more than O odd candies. In other words, an odd candy is a candy with a sweetness level that is not evenly divisible by 2. Additionally, since Supervin is in a rush, he can only eat a single contiguous subset of candies.

Therefore, he wants to eat a contiguous non-empty subset of candies in which there are at most O odd candies and the total sweetness level is maximized, but not more than D. Help Supervin to determine the maximum total sweetness level he can get, or return IMPOSSIBLE if there is no contiguous subset satisfying these constraints.

author: @paulsalmon9313
textdisplay:
I agree. I believe that with any solution on an unsorted array(s), you will still need to check every element. With them being of the same fixed size, that's n^2.

This also caused me to pause and then I did a kind of deep dive on this problem.

Even with the elements sorted, a brute force algorithm is n^2.

Consider::
desired: 70
array1: [50, 51, 52, 53, 54]
array2: [20, 21, 22, 23, 24]

Where we start at the end, or consider a desired number of 78 or greater where we start from the beginning, brute force is o(n^2).

So we would like better if possible.

Other people have posted the same solution, but typing it out helps me :-)

I do like to start with how sorting the data will help me. My thought was with the arrays sorted you can now iterate array1's elements(length 'n' times), then binary search array2 for a number that adds up to our desired number, storing off the closest sum as we go. The binary search on the sorted array2 reduces all array1 operations (n) on array2 to log(n). So we have nlogn.

A bit irrelevant to time complexity but now that I think about it, only one array needs to be sorted.

Zigzagging across the matrix requires 2n - 1 comparisons with the target (count the purple squares and you‚Äôll see this pattern), thus it‚Äôs O(n)

However, the arrays must be sorted first. You‚Äôre never going to have a better worst case than O(nlogn), so the algorithm is overall O(nlogn).

author: @samuelwaller4924
textdisplay: If all you need to do is sort a list of single digit numbers, then regenerating the items like you described will work fine. However, more commonly the actual items you are sorting are larger pieces of data and the numbers you are sorting by are just the result of some comparison function. If you are sorting a list of images by date, you don't just want a sorted list of the dates. You want the dates sorted, but you still need the rest of the data in each item. The way it it is described in the video, the final values are copied directly from the original array. This means that when the number "2" is put in it's sorted position in the final array, it could just as easily be the number 2 as it could be a picture or a user object with an id of 2.

author: @ployapinon6345
textdisplay:
Great explanation! keep up the good work. Love your teaching style very much.

FYI - For anyone who would like a Python version of counting sort based on his explanation.

def counting_sort(arr):
# step 1. find max
mx = max(arr)

# step 2. count frequency and store counts in the 'count' array
count = [0 for _ in range(mx + 1)]
for item in arr:
count[item] += 1

# step 3. compute the max position of each number based on
# the frequency stored in the 'count' array
for i in range(1, len(count)):
count[i] += count[i-1]

# step 4. shift values in 'count' by one to the right
for c in range(len(count)-1, 0, -1):
count[c] = count[c-1]
count[0] = 0

# step 5. fill the result array
res = [0] * len(arr)
for item in arr:
idx = count[item]
res[idx] = item
count[item] += 1

# done!
return res

author: @samuelwaller4924
textdisplay:
In big O notation, only the relative relationship matters. Even though it is 2n, it is always 2n no matter what you put in. That means it can basically be factored out or ignored. Think of f(), which has a runtime of 1, and g which has a run time of 3. Even though g takes longer, they are both O(1) because it is only the relative change in the run time with respect to n. If it take 2n second to to run, what if I redefine 1 second to be twice as long? Then it only takes n seconds, which is O(n). As you can see, when you just look at the relationship they are the same.


It's kind of like how when you take the derivative of a function, any constant terms are removed. Even though x^2 + 3 is 3 more than x^2, we are only looking at the change amount of change which is the same for both.

textdisplay: Why should we choose data anlysis on python over power Bi & tableau?

author: @samuelzietek
textdisplay: If you have access to those tools ,both are great if you already know them well! Both of those require paid accounts and are usually tied to your company. As always, you should follow whatever the team has decided to use so everyone is on the same page, even if it is less efficient. The use case for using python over the other two would be if you already have a lot of python as part of your workflow. I've worked places where they use python over VBA for excel macros and there are a lot of internal tools and applications that use python. The other benefit is you can run these workflows in linux server environments really easily. Lastly, python is a lighter weight solution compared to PowerBI and Tableau. A .py file with these dependencies is much smaller and more portable than the other two. It really depends on your requirements and your use case. One is not necessarily better than the other. There is no "best data analysis tool", you just need the right tool for the job.

author: @LieEurope
textdisplay:
// JS

function kadane(arr) {
let currentMax = arr[0]
let globalMax = currentMax;

for (let i = 1; i < arr.length; i++) {
currentMax = Math.max(arr[i], currentMax + arr[i]);

if (currentMax > globalMax) {
globalMax = currentMax;
}
}

return globalMax;
}

author: @omarrahwanjy4640
textdisplay:
The logic is totally right, but the reason that you're getting a wrong answer that you're always updating the global sum, which is wrong!
You should set the global sum to the maximum between the current and the previous global sum. So, when you get to calculate the max sum of a subarray ending with -2, it would be the max of ({-2}, {3,-2}, {2,3,-2}, {1,2,3,-2}) and the last subarray is the maximum, so the current sum would become 4, but the global sum is 6, so you won't update it.
Next, you'll have to find the max sum of a subarray ending with 5, it is either {5} or {current sum+5}. And the max is {current sum+5}. So, the current sum would be 4+5=9.
Eventually, you have to update the old global 6 with the greater current 9.
And the answer is 9.

hey bro please help me
https://www.codechef.com/problems/SPAMCLAS
in this link i try to solve problem in python and i solved this problem but my script consume much more time
and this problem execution time limit is 2 sec
so , please make video to solve this problem in python

my solution

#Spam Classification Using Neural Net
spammers=list()
non_spammers=list()
n=int(input())
for i in range(n):
spammers.append(0)
non_spammers.append(0)
n=[int(x) for x in input().split()]
neuron,min_x,max_x=n[0],int(n[1]),int(n[2])
weight = list()
bais = list()
for j in range(neuron):
m=[int(x) for x in input().split()]
weight.append(m[0])
bais.append(m[1])
for x in range(min_x,max_x+1):
out=x
for k in range(neuron):
out=(weight[k]*out)+bais[k]
if out%2==0:
non_spammers[i]+=1
else:
spammers[i]+=1
for i in range(len(spammers)):
print(non_spammers[i],spammers[i])

author: @damilarejoshua5257
textdisplay:
Hello, Dojo thanks for sharing this video with everyone. However, the link in the description did not contain the Java source code so I tried this instead.
public class UniversalTrees3 {

public static void main(String[] args) {
// 0
// / \
// 1 0
// / \
// 1 0
// / \
// 1 1

Node node0 = new Node(0);
Node node0R0 = new Node(0);
Node node0L1 = new Node(1);
Node node0R0R0 = new Node(0);
Node node0R0L1 = new Node(1);
Node node0R0L1R1 = new Node(1);
Node node0R0L1L1 = new Node(1);

node0.left = node0L1;
node0.right = node0R0;
node0R0.right = node0R0R0;
node0R0.left = node0R0L1;
node0R0L1.right = node0R0L1R1;
node0R0L1.left = node0R0L1L1;

System.out.println("Sum of Non Empty Universal Trees is 5");
System.out.println(univTotal(node0).total);

}
//solution linear time complexity
static BooleanInt univTotal(Node root) {
if (root == null) {
return new BooleanInt(0, true);
}
BooleanInt leftUniv = univTotal(root.left);
BooleanInt rightUniv = univTotal(root.right);
Boolean isUnival = true;
if ((!leftUniv.isUniv || !rightUniv.isUniv)) {
isUnival = false;
}
if (root.left != null && root.left.data != root.data) {
isUnival = false;
}
if (root.right != null && root.right.data != root.data) {
isUnival = false;
}
if (isUnival) {
return new BooleanInt(leftUniv.total + rightUniv.total + 1, true);
} else {
return new BooleanInt(leftUniv.total + rightUniv.total, false);
}
}
}

class Node {
int data;
Node right;
Node left;
Node(int data) {
this.data = data;
}
}

class BooleanInt {
int total;
Boolean isUniv;
BooleanInt(int total, Boolean isUniv) {
this.total = total;
this.isUniv = isUniv;
}
}

author: @sollertia3161
textdisplay:
You can achieve the same result with this one function in O(n) time:

class Tree:
def __init__(self):
self.node_count = 0

def find_uni_trees(self, root):
if root == None:
return 0
else:
x = True

if ((root.child1 != None and root.child1.data != root.data)
or (root.child2 != None and root.child2.data != root.data)):
x = False

sum = self.find_uni_trees(root.child1) + self.find_uni_trees(root.child2)
self.node_count += 1

if x is True:
if self.node_count - 1 == sum: # If the entire tree is universal
sum += 1
return 1 + sum
else:
return 0 + sum

else:

author: @stentechy3346
textdisplay: Hi @Francesco how can I reach out to you, I'm introverted and finding it hard to grow my social presence, network or land a job.

author: @anoridinaryhumanbeing70
textdisplay:
@@stentechy3346 grab Dale Carneige's famous book..
Follow the advices mentioned therein..

It's actually superbly easy and pretty practical..

I still AM an introvert -- and I love it!
Communication skills have nothing to do with being an introvert or an extrovert.
It can be learnt and practiced. And mastered.

The first step though is not to get nervous -- but be a good listener -- genuinely interested.

And you don't need to be a "Simon Sinek" to break into the tech industry. Just basic articulateness is needed.
As the team would love to work with an emphatic, understanding, expressive and enthusiastic individual.
Now ofcourse, that's not a replacement for technical competency.

The key diff. b/w/ competency and incompetency is "consistency".
